3.6 Analytical Metrics
To support deeper analysis, we will create derived metrics from the cleaned dataset.


Code
energy_clean &lt;- read.csv("data/energy_data.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

fuel_metrics &lt;- energy_clean |&gt;
  dplyr::filter(Dimension == "Fuel") |&gt;
  dplyr::mutate(
    fossil_grp = Category %in% c("Oil", "Coal", "Natural Gas"),
    low_carbon_grp = Category %in% c("Electricity", "Bioenergy", "Other Fuels")
  ) |&gt;
  dplyr::group_by(Country) |&gt;
  dplyr::summarise(
    fossil_fuel_share = sum(Percentage[fossil_grp], na.rm = TRUE),
    low_carbon_share = sum(Percentage[low_carbon_grp], na.rm = TRUE),
    electr_share = sum(Percentage[Category == "Electricity"], na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

sector_metrics &lt;- energy_clean |&gt;
  dplyr::filter(Dimension == "Sector") |&gt;
  dplyr::group_by(Country) |&gt;
  dplyr::summarise(
    indstr_share = sum(Percentage[Category == "Industry"], na.rm = TRUE),
    trnsprt_share = sum(Percentage[Category == "Transport"], na.rm = TRUE),
    bldngs_share = sum(Percentage[Category == "Buildings"], na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

energy_metrics &lt;- dplyr::left_join(fuel_metrics, sector_metrics, by = "Country")


These derived metrics allow the final report to answer stronger analytical questions. For the primary figure, however, the countries will remain in a fixed ASEAN alphabetical order so that the Fuel and Sector panels can be read in parallel without losing comparability across the two views.

Which countries are most dependent on fossil fuels?
Which countries show higher electricity use?
Which countries have energy demand mainly driven by industry?
Are fuel-mix differences linked to sector-demand differences?

This strengthens the project because the improved visualization is not only more readable, but also supports evidence-based interpretation.
